This paper deals with mechanism design problems, which are typically studied in the field of computational game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves analysis of algorithms and approximation ratios, which are common topics in computer science theory (cs.DS). The use of randomized mechanisms and the consideration of worst-case, smoothed, and average-case analysis suggest a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with the specific problem of one-sided matching, which falls under the umbrella of algorithmic mechanism design (cs.EC).
